hor explores the political force of these private narratives with chapters on the Antinomian crisis in Puritan Massachusetts, early national models of gender and marriage in the works of Charles Brockden Brown and Hannah Webster Foster, infanticide narratives and nineteenth-century accounts of motherhood in the work of Harriet Beecher Stowe and Lydia Maria Child, and "re-arranging" marriage in the poetry of Emily Dickinson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361651640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503616516423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503616516/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles